[src:yarn-package/cli] Yarn provides a rich set of command-line commands to help you with various aspects of your Yarn package, including installation, administration, publishing, etc.
[src:yarn-package/cli] Running `yarn` with no command will run `yarn install`, passing through any provided flags.
[src:yarn-package/cli] Running `yarn <script> [<args>]` will run a user-defined `script`.
[src:yarn-package/cli] Running `yarn <command> [<args>]` will run the command, if it is matching a locally installed CLI.
[src:yarn-package/cli] So you don’t need to setup user-defined scripts for simple use cases.
[src:yarn-package/cli] When running multiple instances of yarn as the same user on the same server, you can ensure only one instance runs at any given time (and avoid conflicts) by passing the global flag `--mutex` followed by `file` or `network`.
[src:yarn-package/cli] When using `file` Yarn will write/read a mutex file `.yarn-single-instance` in the current working directory by default.
[src:yarn-package/cli] You can also specify an alternate or global filename.
[src:yarn-package/cli] When using `network` Yarn will create a server at port `31997` by default.
[src:yarn-package/cli] Running `yarn <command> --verbose` will print verbose info for the execution (creating directories, copying files, HTTP requests, etc.).
[src:yarn-package/cli] Specifies a current working directory, instead of the default `./`.
[src:yarn-package/cli] Use this flag to perform an operation in a working directory that is not the current one.
[src:yarn-package/cli] This can make scripts nicer by avoiding the need to `cd` into a folder and then `cd` back out.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] Workspaces are a new way to set up your package architecture that’s available by default starting from Yarn 1.0.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] It allows you to setup multiple packages in such a way that you only need to run `yarn install` once to install all of them in a single pass.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] Add the following in a `package.json` file.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] Note that the `private: true` is required!
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] Workspaces are not meant to be published, so we’ve added this safety measure to make sure that nothing can accidentally expose them.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] After this file has been created, create two new subfolders named `workspace-a` and `workspace-b`.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] Finally, run `yarn install` somewhere, ideally inside the workspace root.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] Please note the fact that `/workspace-a` is aliased as `/node_modules/workspace-a` via a symlink.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] That’s the trick that allows you to require the package as if it was a normal one!
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] You also need to know that the `/workspace-a/package.json#name` field is used and not the folder name.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] This means that if the `/workspace-a/package.json` `name` field was `"pkg-a"`, the alias will be the following: `/node_modules/pkg-a -> /workspace-a` and you will be able to import code from `/workspace-a` with `const pkgA = require("pkg-a");` (or maybe `import pkgA from "pkg-a";`).
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] Yarn’s workspaces are the low-level primitives that tools like Lerna can (and do!) use.
[src:yarn-package/lang-workspaces] They will never try to support the high-level feature that Lerna offers, but by implementing the core logic of the resolution and linking steps inside Yarn itself we hope to enable new usages and improve performance.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:yarn-package/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:yarn-package/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
