[src:yarn-package/page] The Yarn organization is a collaboration of many companies and individuals dedicated to improving your package management experience.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] While bootstrapped by tech companies, the project was setup from the get go as its own GitHub organization, and eventually became fully autonomous in 2019, following its lead maintainer as he left Facebook for Datadog.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] In 2020 the Yarn team released a major update, Yarn 2.0, also codenamed "Berry".
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] This version came with a full rewriting of both the codebase (which migrated to TypeScript in the process) and test suite.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Many features were introduced, a cleaving one being a new unique installation strategy called Yarn Plug'n'Play.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Under this default but optional mode, Yarn wouldn't generate a `node_modules` folder anymore, instead opting to generate a single Node.js resolver file named `.pnp.cjs`.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] While justified by the Yarn team as a need to address multiple design flaws in the typical Node.js module resolution, this change required some support from other projects in the ecosystem which took some time to materialise, adding friction to the migration from Yarn 1.22. to Yarn 2.0.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Users can write their own plugins for Yarn.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Yarn constraints allow users to enforce rules for their dependencies or manifest fields across scoped workspaces.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Downloaded packages are cached and stored as a single file.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Plug'n'Play allows users to run Node projects without `node_modules` folder, defining the way or location to resolve dependencies package files with the Plug-n-Play-control file.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] This feature is aimed to fix an unwell structured `node_modules` architecture and resulting in a faster Node.js application start-up time.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Plugins can add new resolvers, fetchers, linkers, commands, and can also register to some events or be integrated with each other, most features of Yarn are implemented through plugins, including `yarn add` and `yarn install`, which are also preinstalled plugins.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Users can define which protocol will be used to resolve certain packages, for example, the *git* protocol is used for downloading a public package from a Git repository, and the *patch* protocol is used for creating a patched copy of the original package.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Release Workflow automatically upgrades relative packages among monorepos workspaces when root packages are upgraded.
[src:yarn-package/yarn-package-manager] Workspaces allow multiple projects to work together in the same repository and automatically apply changes to other relatives when source code is modified, allowing installation of multiple packages in a single pass by running the installation command only once.
